This project is a fully self‑hosted Raspberry Pi 5 home server, designed for reliability, efficiency, and long‑term expandability. It uses a dedicated SATA SSD for the operating system and a high‑speed NVMe SSD for media and container storage, following the same architecture used in professional server environments.

The system runs entirely on Docker, allowing each service to operate in its own isolated container for stability, easy updates, and clean management. With Gigabit Ethernet, Wi‑Fi 6 support, and 24/7‑ready hardware, the Raspberry Pi 5 serves as a compact but powerful always‑on server.

Core Capabilities
Media Server — Streams movies, TV shows, music, and photos from the NVMe SSD

Private VPN — Secure remote access to the home network

Docker Host — Runs multiple isolated services efficiently

Pi‑hole DNS Server — Blocks ads and trackers for the entire network

Future Expansion — Additional containers and services as needed

Hardware Architecture
The server is built using:

Raspberry Pi 5 (8GB) — The main compute unit, capable of running multiple services simultaneously

120GB SATA SSD — Dedicated OS drive for Raspberry Pi OS, Docker, configs, logs, and system data

1TB NVMe SSD — High‑speed media and container storage for Jellyfin, Home Assistant backups, databases, and large files

Elecrow Mini PC Case — Provides cooling, NVMe support, airflow, and physical protection

SATA‑to‑USB 3.0 Adapter — Connects the OS SSD to the Pi with fast, reliable USB 3.0 speeds

Cat 6 Ethernet Cable — Ensures stable gigabit networking for streaming and automation

CyberPower UPS — Protects against power loss, corruption, and electrical spikes

Anti‑Static Mat — Prevents electrostatic discharge during assembly

Arctic MX‑6 Thermal Paste — Improves CPU cooling and long‑term thermal stability

Project Goals
This home server is designed to be:

Reliable — Protected by a UPS, cooled properly, and built for 24/7 uptime

Fast — NVMe storage for media, SATA SSD for OS, Gigabit Ethernet for streaming

Modular — Docker containers keep services clean, isolated, and easy to manage

Expandable — Additional services can be added without reconfiguring the system

Professional — Mirrors the architecture of real servers with separate OS and data drives
